title: For Sale:  More Freedom!
postcontent: HB 210 has been assigned to the House Judiciary Committee. Now is the time to start making phone calls. Call the Legislative Message line at 1-REDACTED and tell them that your message is for "All the members of the House Judiciary Committee" and your message is "Give HB 210 a hearing in the House Judiciary Committee and send it to the floor with a favorable report". I have spoken to many senators and representatives that are pro-gun and want such bills to pass, but they say that Kentuckians just don't call in support, and the voices of opposition outnumber the few who call. So if you want to not only protect our gun rights, but advance them, you need to call and make your voice heard to your representative. A right not exercised is lost. Hell, get your friends and family to call also!The House Judiciary Committee is Chaired by Joe Fischer. Representative Fischer is a fair and honorable man. He will give the bill a fair hearing if he senses enough support for it. There are some very anti-gun people on that committee that will fight this bill. Expect to see them try to attach several stupid amendments to it. We can win this fight and get this bill passed, but we have to fight and fight smart. This is the first bill we have had in several years that affects all concealed carry licensees. If this passes, the ban on guns will stop on public college campuses, there will no longer be any gun bans in city and county buildings, except detention facilities and court facilities. You would be able to carry at a city council meeting, a Fiscal Court meeting and at a meeting of the General Assembly. The "mad mommies" will be up in arms about this bill. They will call day and night. Don't let them "out call" us. Get your friends and neighbors to call and everybody call often. Call your individual Representative (http://www.lrc.ky.gov/Find%20Your%20Legislator/Find%20Your%20Legislator.html )and tell them to do all they can to get Chairman Fischer to give this bill a hearing. It has a real chance of passing!I also urge you to oppose HB-31, HR-68, HB-189, and HB-209. HB-31 is a bill that would criminalize leaving firearms unsecured. This is a slippery slope that leads to laws like they have in California, where all guns in a home must be unloaded and locked in a safe and all ammunition is to be locked in a separate safe in another room. HR-68 and HB-189 would remove the Kentucky legislature’s preemptive authority on firearms regulation and let local governments make their own laws.  Such a bill would harm Kentuckians all over the state as they visit Louisville, Lexington, and other cities that hold a less than favorable view on armed citizens. Finally, HB-209 would make anyone convicted of a hate crime prohibited from buying or possessing a firearm. And we all know how loose the standards for labeling something as a “hate crime” are.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer 522 .22LR Rifle with Red Dot, Drum Magazine and Bull Barrel
postcontent: Selling my Sig Sauer 522 .22LR rifle. Great firearm based on the original Sig 551 and more recent Sig 556 designs, it allows training with low cost ammunition on a firearm that shares the same form and controls as its big brothers. It's designed from the ground up as a .22LR and is not some sort of retrofit, and as such it's exceedingly reliable. It's a 16.5" barrel on a blowback mechanism, and uses full size style .22LR magazines rather than the thin mags found on many other .22LR rifles. They fit into the same style pouches as traditional AR and AK magazines.The gun is the Classic version which has a polymer fore end barrel shroud, full length top picatinny rail and birdcage style barrel flash hider. It also comes with an adjustable length stock which folds, allowing for close quarters usage or compact transport. I have a Bushnell Trophy 1x28mm multi-reticule red dot scope mounted to the top rail. It has red and green backlighting modes with multiple intensities as well as three reticule styles (dot, cross and ring). Very easy to use in any condition and quick acquisition from 1-100 yards.It comes with three 25-round magazines, one Sig Sauer branded Black Dog magazine and two grey CMMC magazines. It also includes a 50-round drum magazine by Black Dog. These are hard to find and usually run about $75 just on their own. Super fun!I also have an additional bull barrel and barrel wrench that will go with it, which allows for more consistent target shooting due to better heat dissipation. I never used it, and there is some very light surface oxidation near the end of the barrel. It's purely cosmetic and hard to notice. I'll try to take some cleaner to it. These usually sell for about $150.All of this fits into the factory hard case, which has the original manual and paperwork that shipped with it. The rifle and scope are in great shape, no notable nicks or scratches. Little bit of powder residue left on the flash hider and some residue on the internals. It's had about 2,000 rounds put through it with only a handful of failures to fire. For 22LR that's pretty great, and the only stuff to give it a spot of grief was bulk Remington Thunderbolts, to the surprise of nobody.These rifles are great firearms and are becoming harder to find. Those who have them tend to keep them, and I'm in no hurry to part with it, but wanted to test the waters.I'm asking $750 OBO for the rifle and all accessories. Hard case, accessories, red dot scope, three magazines plus drum mag and the heavy target barrel. I have a variety of .22LR available separately if you wanted something to shoot along with it, let me know if you need some and we can figure out any additional cost for it.Cash only, local sales only. I can deliver between Anchorage and the valley areas.Thanks!
